{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937120601/0593.xml":{"full_text":"Ebb Tide Felt After\nFour Years of Repeal;\nStates Go Dry Locally\nFOUR YEAR8 AFTER REPEAL\nRetail\nSale by\nLicense\nState Monopoly\n\nDry aa Retards\n\"Hard\u201d liquor\nFour years after repeal, the \"hard-liquor\u201d tide has covered almost the\nentire country. The six states In white are the only ones with state\nlaws prohibiting liquor today, and none of even these states has an ab\nsolutely \"bone-dry\u201d law. Of the liquor states, 28 hold to a licensing sys\ntem, 14 to state monopolies. None has switched control systems since\nrepeal.\nBY WILLIS THORNTON\nNEA Service SUIT Correspondent\nThe repeal tide which was let\nloose on December 5, 1933 appear:\nto be reaching Its crest. There b\nevidence that under the surface a\ndefinite ebb tide has set In.\nFour years after repeal, here are\nsome of the interesting develop\nments:\nAlabama in 1937 became the 42nd\nstate to permit sale of \"hard\u201d liquor\nSix states are still dry as regard:\nstate liquor laws. Georgia license:\nsale of beer and domestic wine only\nKansas and Oklahoma permit only\n3.2 beer, Tennessee 5 per cent, Mis\nsissippi permits local option on 4\nper cent beer. North Carolina, dry\nstate-wide, permits counties to sell\nliquor if they wish.\nGradually Go Dry\nOf the 28 states (and the District\nof Columbia) which have license\nsystems and the 14 states which\nhave state monopolies, none has\nswitched systems snlce repeal.\nMany \"wet\u201d states are gradually\ngoing dry locally. Ohio Is \"wet,\u201d but\nalready 18 per cent of her people\nlive under some form of county ot\ntownship prohibition.\nKentucky, home of bourbon, has\nprohibition In almost a third of Its\ncounties. That recalls the situation\nJust before national prohibition In\n1920.\nRepresentative John J. Cochran\nof Missouri, surveying these dry\npatches on the map and comparing\nthem with congressional districts,\nadmits that \"It would not take a\ngroat deal of agitation to foment\na formidable prohibition move\nment in Congress.\u201d\nDry organizations are taking on\nnew life. Their campaigns today\nare streamlined, using the latest\nIn movies, radio and other means\nof persuasion. Some are working\nunder the slogan \"Prohibition by\n1940.\u201d The rise in automobile\ndeath tolls gives them their best\nargument since 1919.\nBillion Dollars Invested\nIn the meantime, a million men\nhave been given jobs and a bil\nlion dollars have been invested In\nthe liquor and beer business.\nMore than two billion dollars in\ntax revenue have gone into na\ntional, state, and local treasuries\nfrom liquor and beer.\nLiquor production has at last\nfilled the gap required for storage\nand aging. Now it will level off\nto approximately the rate of con\nsumption. During these four years\nalmost a half billion gallons of\nwhiskey have gone to the bonded\nwarehouses.\nNothing Is Ever Settled\nThe \"big-time\" bootlegging that\nfhade a shambles of the \u201920\u2019s is\ngone. But bootlegging is by no\nmeans gone. No one knows how\nmuch liquor is bootlegged. Esti\nmates vary all the way from 15\nto 40 per cent. Some bootlegging\nIs \u201cbig\u201d enough so that 98 people\nwere Indicted in one Philadelphia\nring. The revenuers are still\nseizing a half-million gallons of\nillicit booze each year.\nThus, four years after repeal,\nnothing has been settled about the\nliquor problem excepting the fact\nthat nothing Is ever settled about\nthe liqour problem.\n\u201cPerfect Crime\u201d Not\nPerfect, Says Doran\nFormer Waterburian Investigating $50,000 Regis*\ntered Mail Theft in New York Last Week\nInspector James J. Doran of the\npostofflce department, a former local\nman, Is one of the leading Investi\ngators of the $50,000 registered mall\ntheft which took place last week In\nNew York. Confident that the \"per\nfect crime\" was not perfect, Inspec\ntor Doran told reporters, \u201cWe'll find\nout how It was done, and when we\ndo It will turn out to be very sim\nple.\"\nThe mall was stolen from a truck\nPAPER RESPECTS\nTHEIR PRIVACY\nBoston. Dec. 6\u2014(UPi.\u2014The Bos\nton Herald today published on Its\nfront page a two-column box con\ntaining a 135-word story on the re\nturn of Colonel and Mrs. Charles A.\nLindbergh to America and this ex\nplanation\n\u201cIn view of the desire of the Lind\nberghs for privacy, the Herald this\nmorning prints none of the many\nphotographs of them fleeing toward\ntlielr car or those furtively taken\nwhile they were dining on shipboard.\nNor does the Herald feel It neces\nsary to print the news stories\ntheorizing on the reasons for their\nvisit and describing their attempts\nto avoid publicity.\"\nwhich was enroute from Pennsyl\nvania state post office to the Lacka\nwanna terminal at Hoboken.\nInspector Doran started his career\nin the postal department as a car\nrier for the Waterbury post office.\nHe has participated in numerous\nimportant cases including the\nBrooklyn mail truck holdup, which\nnetted the robbers $400,000.\nInspector Doran was born here in\nthe Doran homestead at Doolittle\nalley and entered the postal service\nj in 1914. He was assigned to the\nSt. Louis division and then to New\nYork. His earliest work was done\nat Glens Palls and then later about\nthe Adironadck mountains and\nWestchester county.\nPour years ago he was made head\nof the New York division, compris\ning 72 men. Most of his work has\nj been in fraud cases.\nCRIME WAVE STRIKES RAND\nJohannesburg <U.P.)\u2014 A crime\ni wave in Johannesburg and other\nj Rand towns has led to a general rc\nI armament of the citizens in the past\ntwo months. Holdups occur nearly\nevery day in some of these towns,\nand motorists arc warned against\nmarauders on the high roads.\nHOLD EVERYTHING.' cl,d.BU.\nCOMPENSATION\nBENEFITS HELP\nThey Will Serve to Put\nBlock to Advance of\nDepression\nWashington, Dec. 6 (UP)\nGovernment officials are counting\non unemployment compensation\nbenefits of as much as a million\ndollars a day after Jan. 1 to help\nsolve the problem of Increasing\nunemployment, it was learned to\nday.\nPayments of benefits to unem\nployed under the social security\nlaws begin in 21 states and the\nDistrict of Columbia on Jan. 1. By\nJuly 1, 1039, all 48 states will have\nunemployment compensation.\nHarry Hopkins, Works Progress\nAdministrator, returns late today\nand Is expected to carry out In\nstructions received from President\nRoosevelt regarding relief during\ntheir fishing trip oS the Florida\ncoast.\nKeep Relief Drive\nThe administration Is committed\nto keeping relief payments for the\ncurrent fiscal year ending June 30\nwithin the 81,500,000,000 appropriated\nbut It Is also on record as saying\nthat none of the unemployed shall\nstarve. If unemployment becomes\nwide-spread, one of these pledges\nmust buckle. v\nWPA relief rolls have increased\nonly seasonally during the past\nfew weeks although officials esti\nmated Informally that a million\nworkers have lost their Jobs during\nthe business recession. The most\nrecent Increase of more than 10,000\nsent the WPA total above the 1,\n500,000 mark.\nHalf of Country\nOn January 1, unemployment <jpm\npensatlon swings Into operation In\nalmost half of the country\u2019s states.\nNow It operates only In Wisconsin,\nthe pioneer state In social security\nlegislation. Slightly more than 11,\n500,000 workers in the 22 Jurisdic\ntions will be covered by these com\npensation laws.\nTreasury statistics reveal that dur\ning November approximately $83,\n000,000 came In on unemployment\ncompensation collections. More than\nhalf a billion dollars has been paid\ninto the funds and much of this will\nbe available for payments after Jan\nuary X.\nVital Factor in Relief\nGovernment relief officials admit\nted that the benefits would be a vital\nfactor In the relief picture after the\nfirst of the year. They are banking\non these benefits to stop a march\nfor WPA relief funds If the business\nrecession becomes serious during the\nwinter months.\nStates which will launch unem\nployment compensation after Jan. 1\nand the number of persons covered\nby state laws Include:\nConnecticut, 408,000; Maine, 132,\n000; Massachusetts, 851,000; New\nHampshire, 93,000; New York, 2,\n646,000; Rhode Island, 169,000; Ver\nmont, 44,000.\nBehind The\nLines\nLegion Corp$\nRaymond W. Walker, comman\nder of Corp. Coyle post, American\nLegion, Fife, Drum A Bugle Corps,\nhas been reelected to that office\nfor the fifth consecutive time. Wil\nliam Boisvert, vice-commander and\nfinance officer and Olln H. Barrie,\nadjutant, were also relected at the\ncorps\u2019 annual meeting in the Le\ngion Home last week. Reports of\nofficers indicated that the corps\nenjoyed one of its most successful\nyears In history. Its participation\nIn the national convention parade\nIn New York City last September\nwas the high-light of the year.\nBon Voyage!\nMr. and Mrs. Jack Marshall\nwho sail Friday for a two months\nvisit to Scotland, were honored by\nmembers of Lord Kitchener Post,\nBritish War Veterans, with a\nbon-voyage party held Saturday\nnight at the Chapter hall on Sco\nvllle street. Members of the Edith\nCavell Post of Ansonla, Gen. Al\nlenby Post of Hartford and boos\nters of the American Soccer team,\nalso attended.\nDuring the progress of events\nCommander Donald MacDonald\nmade the presentation of a gift\nto the honored couple. Gifts were\nalso presented to Mr. and Mrs.\nThomas Sullivan who were recent\nly married.\nWadhanu Camp\nOfficers were elected at the an\nnual meeting of Wadhams camp\nauxiliary, Sons of Union Veterans,\nlast week, with Mrs. Irene Mack\nchosen president. Others chosen\nwere: Vice president, Mrs. Clara\nPlant; chaplain, Mrs. Alice Mar\ntin; treasurer, Mrs. Lettle Flood;\nsecretary, Mrs. Ethel Plercy; guide,\nMrs. Mary Jackson; assistant\nguide, Mrs. Lena Mallory; color\nbearers, Mrs. Carrie Clark and\n\u25a0Mrs. Katherine Turrell; Inside\nguard, Mrs. Rosalie Ball; musician\nMrs. Plercey; trustees, Mrs. Lura\nE. Duttgn. Mrs. Jackson and Mrs.\nMartin. Mrs. Flood was named\ndelegate to the national encamp\nment and Mrs. Dutton, alternate.\nMrs. Plant was chosen delegate\nto the state convention and Mrs.\nJackson, alternate. The next meet\ning will be held December 17.\nNEW JERSEY WILL\nHAVE LABOR PARTY\nNewark, N. J., Dec. 8. (UP)\u2014\nAmerican Federation of Labor and\nCommittee for Industrial Organiza\ntion Unions Joined today In the\nformation of a political party\npledged to fight \u201ccorrupt political\nmachines financed by tory Interests\nand maintained for their benefit.\"\nRepresentatives of 184 unions, in\ncluding 112 affiliated with the CIO\nand 34 A. 7. of L. units, adopted In\nconvention yesterday a resolution\ncreating the American Labor Party\nof New Jersey. A 42-man committee\nwas appointed to work out details\nof organization for consideration at\na second convention within six\nmonths.\nThe resolution creating the new\nparty attacked Mayor Prank Hague,\nThen One Won Laurels And Two Lost Lives\nListening to S. J. Wittman, center, describe the maneuvers he intended using to defeat them ta the Silva\nTrophy race, seemed a good Joke to Rudy Kling, Lemont, I1L, left, and Frank Haines, Detroit, right, shown\nabove at Miami, Fla., before they took off in the 13th event of the annual air show. A few minutes later\nKling and Haines were dead, Instantly as their tiny speedsters plunged to the earth, out of control at the\nfirst pylon. Wlttman, of Oshkosh, Wls, won the event. _\nMissionary Asks\nFriends Here To.\nAssist Indians\nCharitable Waterburians\u2014and\nthey are many of them as rec\nords will Indicate\u2014have an ex\ntra opportunity this year to make\nthe Christmas season a hapy one\ntor children. When they have ob\nserved the maxim. \u201cCharity Be\ngins at Home\" and have remem\nbered little ones In far away for\neign missions as they have been\naccustomed to, If their means will\npermit and their generous nature\nsupplies the urge, they can make\nthe Uletlde season a memorable\none for descendants of real Amer\nicans\u2014little Indian babes out In\nSouth Dakota. A number of Wa\nerburlans have already contrib\nuted to the happiness fund. They\nwill be greatly appreciated by\ntheir spiritual leader, Father\nHolmes, whose letter to local\nfriends reads as follows:\nThe child Jesus calls on you\nthis Christmas in the person of a\nlittle Indian of the plains.\nWho Is not moved by the good\nexample of the three wise Kings\ncoming from afar with gifts to\ntheir new born King.\nThe Divine Babe however re\ngards whatever is done to the\nleast of His little ones as done to\nHimself.\nWon\u2019t you help us then to glad\nen their hearts this Christmas\nby sending, clothing for young\nor old, who are poorly clad, shoes,\nmaterials for clothing, any arti\ncles, household, playthings your\nchildren\u2019s last year\u2019s Christmas\narticles, clothing which you and\u2019\nthe children have grown out\nof, money of course too, any use\nful donations will be heartily wel\ncome and appreciated.\nI will not forget to pray for you\ntogether with my ISO Indian chil\ndren and over 300 grown up In\ndians and shall oiler up one of\nmy Christmas Masses for you.\nWith my best wishes for the\nHoly Season.\nFATHER WILLIAM HOLMES,S.C.J.\nCheyenne Agency, South Dakota.\nBasketball League\nOpens This Evening\nSuperintendent of Parks to Officiate at Ceremonies;\n\u201c45\u201d Tournament Also on Tonight\u2019s Program\nAppropriate Ceremonies have been\narranged for the opening tonight of\nthe Washington Park senior basket\nball league. Five guests have been\ninvited to witness the two games\nthe first of which will be started at\n7:30 o\u2019clock.\nThe first of the two games will be\nthat between the Companionship\nclub (a new entry) and the Robins;\nand the feature attraction lists the\nReymond Hillles against the Welles.\nAll teams are reported to be stronger\nthan they were last year, and an\nother whirlwind league is in the\noffing.\nQuests will include Parks Supt.\nJames J. Curtin, who will toss up\nthe first ball; Thomas Moore, sec\nretary of the park board; Rev. David\nM. O\u2019Keefe of St. Francis Xavier\u2019s\nparish; Ex-Gov. Charles A. Temple\nton and Rov. Robert Foster of the\nSouth Federated church.\nJohn McCormack is to referee the\nopening games.\n\u201c45\u201d Tonight\nIt\u2019s up to Creaven tonight to blast\nLOYALISTS Kill\nFRENCH FARMER\nPerpignan, France, Dec. 6.\u2014(UP).\n\u2014Spanish Loyalist soldiers, pursuing\na deserter from the civil war, crossed\nthe border into France today and\nshot and killed a French farmer sus\npected of harboring the fugitive.\nThe death of the farmer, Sebastian\nJuanola, was reported by local po\nlice to Paris diplomatic sources\nwhich are expected to conduct an\ninvestigation. Juanola was said to be\na cousin of the soldier who crossed\nthe mountains to avoid lighting on\nthe Aragon front. Republican Cara\nbineers who tracked him to the farm\nescaped across the border after the\nshooting.\nHighway Department\nPlans New Projects\n48 Miles of Road Construction, 15 Bridges Remain to\nBe Completed as Part of 1937\u2019s Program\nWhen the year 1937 ends this\nmonth, the state highway depart\nment will have under contract the\nconstruction of IS bridges and the\nsurface Improvement of 48 miles of\nhighway to carry over for comple\ntion Into 1938, Highway Commis\nsioner John A. Macdonald stated to\nday. This work, therefore, will con\nstitute the start of the department\u2019s\n1938 program which will be supple\nmented by extensive projects now\nbeing planned and to be contracted\nfor next spring and summer.\nWhile winter weather makes It\nnecessary in Connecticut to suspend\nhighway construction operations, ex\ncept for grading and drainage jobs,\nthe department Is kept busy during\nthe winter months drafting plans\nand specifications and otherwise pre\nparing for the next construction\nseason, Commissioner Macdonald\nsaid. While employment by con\ntractors engaged In road building\nwill naturally drop considerably\nfrom the 2,000 employed by them\nlast month, the maintenance forces\nof the department will be kept In\ntact to provide for snow removal,\nguarding against Ice conditions and\nemergency winter repairs.\nMerritt Parkway\nOf the total number of bridge\nprojects and the mileage of surface\njobs to be carried over Into 1938,\nfive of the bridges and 19 miles of\nthe surface work are on the Mer\nritt Parkway. These bridges Include\nthe big 130-foot span, steel arch\nbridge over the Saugutuck river at\nWestport; the 60-foot, structure\nsteel span over the parkway at West\nRocks road In Norwalk; and smaller\nhighway grade separation structures\nin Norwalk and Fairfield. There\nare four paving projects, running\nfrom Greenwich Into Trumbull, to\nbe carried over on the parkway. In\nall cases, the projects call for con\ncrete pavement 52 feet wide with a\nparkway In the middle. There are\nalso three grading projects in Nor\nwalk, Westport and Fairfield, plus\nshort lengths of paving.\nBridge Building\nOther slseable bridge construction\nprojects to be completed next year\nInclude the following; The big Mld\ndletown-Portland bridge over the\nConnecticut river; the bridge over\nLake Whitney on Whitney avenue,\nHamden, an alternate College Hlgh\nwhose Jersey city Democratic ma\nchine Is one of the most powerful In\nthe country, and Gov. Harold G.\nHoffman, who will be succeeded\nnext month by U. S. Senator JL\nHarry Moore, Democrat,\nway route out or New Haven; tne\nbig railroad grade separation proj\nect In Newington; a railroad over\nhead crossing In North Canaan; a\n130-foot, twin span, structure at\nTaftvllle; and the 141-foot, twin\nspan bridge over the New Haven\nrailroad and Its 60-foot mate over\nthe Central Vermont railroad In\nWindham.\nExcept for sizeable macadam pav\ning Jobs In Barkhamsted, East\nGranby and Enfield, most of the\nsurfacing work to be carried over\nInto 1938 will consist of gravel jobs\non local roads.\ncontinue to Christmas Day, accord\ning to the committee\u2019s chairman, Rev\nClalreF. Yohe. It Is expected the\nsale will exceed Its quota before the\nend of this week, so prompt has\nbeen the response\nThe next meeting of Litchfield\ngrange will take place Thursday\nevening.\nSchool Notes\nCROSBY\nPlans for the next issue of The\nArgus will be made at a meeting of\nthe staff this afternoon at 3 o\u2019clock\nin room 317.\nThe Home Economics club will\nmeet tomorrow at 1:30 in room 210\nfor a business session, following\nwhich they will make a visit to the\nConnecticut Light St Power com\nI pany for a cooking demonstration.\nThe faculty advisors are Miss Ma\nbel Jordan and Miss Elizabeth\nWhltehlll.\nThe Occupations club, headed by\nRoy Walcb, Is planning a visit to\nthe Naugatuck Rubber Company.\nThe Camera club will meet today\nat the close of school In room 304.\nThe Glee club will meet today,\ngirls at 2 o\u2019clock and boys at 7:15\np. m. All meetings are In the as\nsembly hall.\nSwimming practice for 3 o\u2019clock\nthis afternoon has been called by\nCoach J. O. P. Manherz.\nThe Art Club will meet tomorrow\nat 3 o'clock.\nLEAVENWORTH\nEye tests were taken by the pu\npils of Leavenworth high school to\nday.\nMiss Anna Meehan swimming In\nstructress was absent today due to\nIllness.\nMarriages In Germany this year\nnumbered more than In the corres\nponding period at 1936.\nJohn Fitzmaurlce's snamrocxs irom\nthe lead In the St. Francis Xavier\nHoly Name society \"45\u201d tournament.\nThe scehedule places the following\ngames: Fitzmaurice against Creaven,\nMcHugh against Bowey, Coughlin\nagainst O\u2019Donnell, and Fargeau\nagainst Cusick.\nForty Hours Devotion\nThe forty hours devotion will start\nat St. Francis Xavier's church next\nSunday after the 11 o\u2019clock mass.\nParishioners are requested to provide\nflowers for the altar.\nFraternal\nNews\nB. P. O. E.\nThe memory of members of the\nWaterbury Lodge of Elks who died\nduring the past year were honor\ned during memorial services held\nlast night in the chapel of the\nledge rooms on West Main street,\nat which time a capacity attend\nance was present.\nThe feature of the program was\nthe eulogy delivered by Theodore\nV. Meyer. Exalted Ruler James\nF. Neagle opened the ceremony\nand Frank H. Bailey, chaplain,\noffered the prayer and benedic\ntion. \u201cSome Where a Voice Is\nCalling\u2019\u2019 and \u201cA Rosary I Wrought\nfor You,\u201d were sung by Harry\nMatthleu, Eugene T. Oviatt ac\ncompanied at the organ for the\ngroup singing of \u201cStar Spangled\nBanner\u201d and \u201cOld Lang Syne.\"\nThose whose memory was\nhonored were Dr. Daniet F. Don\nahue, Frank W. Doyle, Frank\nJ. Gatter, Jr., Francis Fruin, Wil\nliam J. Freeman, Henry W.\nO\u2019Connor, James W. Carroll, Ar\nthur D. Worden, Joseph E. Fortin,\nAndrew M. Larson, John Mori\narity, Enoch J. Ashley, Truman\nS. Lewis, Frank A. Fierce, James\nMurphy and Joseph A. Linehan.\nKnights Of Columbus\nOfficers of Sheridan council, 24,\nKnights of Columbus, will confer\nwith District Deputy John F. Rob\ninson tomorrow night at 8 o'clock.\nImmediately preceding the regular\nmeeting of the council at the Col\numbus club, 79 North Main street.\nAll officers are requested to be\npresent promptly.\nDuring the meeting the first de\ngree will be exemplified upon a\nclass of 15 candidates with officers\nof Sheridan council participating\nin the ritual.\nThis is the first class to be re\nceived into the order since, the\ncouncil launched its membership\ndrive here this fall. It is expected\nthat it will be but one of many\nclasses to be initiated in the com\ning months. In tonight\u2019s K. of C.\nbroadcast from WATR at 6:15\nJohn P. Kinney, Crosby high\nschool Instructor, will be the guest\nspeaker. He will speak on the\nbenefits of K. of C. membership,\nand the ideals of the order.\nTomorrow night\u2019s degree will be\nthe first exemplified under Grand\nKnight Thomas W. Scadden\u2019s ad\nministration and is to be followed\nshortly by the second degree, at\nwhich time it is also hoped to ex\nemplify the first degree again on\nanother group of candidates.\nPlans for a third degree are now\nbeing discussed by officers of the\ncouncil.\nCosmopolitan Club\nOfficers of the newly organized\nCosmopolitan club will be Installed\nby Coach James Lee of Wllby\nHigh school, at a dinner meeting\nin Bosco's Grill, tomorrow night,\ni The officers are: President, Ralph\ni Mlnervlno; vice-president, Henry\nDelPo; secretary, Pompeii Lentinl\nand treasurer, Peter Masone.\nSyria-American\nOfficers were elected and fifteen\nnew members enrolled at a meet\ning of the local Syrian-American\norganisation auxiliary which took\nplace last Saturday night. An\nother meeting of the chapter will\nbo held Thursday night at the\nhome of Mrs. David Hajjar of Wil\nlow street.\nThe slate elected includes: Mrs.\nGeorge Haddad, president; Mrs.\nGeorge Wlhby, vice-president;\nMrs. Katherine Nejsme, treasur\ner; and Mrs. Salim Rlzik, secre\ntary.\nLIGHTNING ROD COMBS BACK\nDallas, Tex. (UP)\u2014The once po\npular lightning rod Is staging a\ncomeback under the sponsorship ol\nthe Texas fire Insurance commis\nsion. The lightning rod is so well\nthought of by fire Insurance com\npanies that they give reduction In\nrates on rural homes equipped with\napproved types.\nMarket In Irregular\nMood At Start Today\nTrading Was Very Dull\u2014Most of Changes Were Frac\ntional-Losses, However, Were in the Majority\ni\nJ\nn ELMER C. WALTER\n(Hatted Pres* Financial Editor)\nNew York, Dec. 6.\u2014(UP)\u2014Stocks\nand bonds opened irregular in dull\ntrading today. Cotton futures were\nunchanged to 4 points lower.\nMost net changes on the stock\nboard were fractional. Losses were\nIn the majority although there was\nno particular pressure. Some trad\ners took profits on the theory that\nthe market was entitled to a techni-\ncal setback after last week\u2019s recov\nery.\nUnited .States Steel common lost a\npoint to 57 1-2 on 1,000 shares. Other\nsteels dipped smaller amounts with\nBethlehem at 53 3-4 off 1-4.\nChrysler dipped 1-4 to 58 1-4 on\nthe first sale and General Motors\nlost 5-8 to 35 3-8.\nMost railroad issues declined frac\n1:15 P. M. PRICES\nWHITEHOUSE CO.\nAllied Chem.\nAm. Can\nAm. 8m. Ref..\nAm. Tel. dr Tel.\nAnaconda Cop..\nAtch. Top. dr S. F.\nBalt. dr Ohio\nBeth. Steel\nBorden\nCan. Pacific\nCase Mach.\nChes. Ohio\nChrysler Motor\nConsolidated Oil.\nCon. Edison\nContinental Can.\nCorn Products\nDuPont\nEastman Kodak\nElec. Auto-Lite\nFreeport Texas\nGeneral Elec.\nGeneral Foods\nGeneral Motors\nGoodyear\nInt\u2019l Tel. dr Tel.\nJohns Manville.\nKennecot Cop.\nKresge Stores.\nKroger Groceries\nMcKesson dr Robbins.\nMack Truck\nMont. Ward\nMurray Corp.:.\nNash dr Kelvinator.\nNat'l Biscuit.\nNat\u2019l Dairy\nNat\u2019l Pow. dr L.\nN. Y. Central\nNorth Am.\nPackard Motors.\nPenn. R.\nPub. Ser. of N. J.\nPullman Co.\nRadio\nRep. Iron dr Steel\nSears-Roebuck\nSouth Pac.\nStandard Brands\nS. O. of N. J.\nSocony-Vacuum\nStewart-Wamer\nStudebaker\nTexas Corp.\nUnion Carbide.\nUnion Pacific.\nUnited Air\nUnited Corp.\nUnited Gas Improved.\nU. S. Indus. Alcohol.\nU. S. Rubber\nU. S. Steel\nVanadium\nWarner Bros.\nWestern Union\nWestinghouse Elec.\nWoolworth\n163\n83 H\n49%\n150%\n31%\n41%\n12%\n53%\n17%\n8%\n97\n39%\n59%\n30%\n26%\n42\n60%\n119%\n159\n20%\n22%\n43%\n32\n35%\n22\n7\n83%\n37\n16\n16%\n53%\n8%\n22\n36\n6%\n10%\n19%\n14%\n8%\n19%\n23%\n4%\n22%\n35%\n34%\n7%\n18%\n57%\n21%\n8%\n45%\n15%\n10%\n5%\n42%\n71%\n88%\n21%\n3%\n10%\n20%\n28%\n57%\n16%\n7%\n27%\n108%\n38%\nNEW YORK CURB\nAmer. Superpower 1%\nCities Service. 2\nElc. Bond dr Share 11%\nNiagara Hudson Power. 9\nN. Y. Bank Trait Stock*\nThe R. F. Griggs Co.\nBid\n,nk of Manhattan 23\n,nk of N. Y. dr Trust 370\n.nkers Trust 47%\nnt. Hanover Bank dr\nrrust 88\nlase National Bank.. 30\nlemlcal Bank dr Trust 42\nrn Exchange Bank 47\naplre 